<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: AZUSA; 
</P>
<P>
NARANJO MAY QUIT PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Councilman Anthony Naranjo said he has tentatively decided to step down as 
chairman of the city's Drug and Gang Task Force and as City Council liaison 
with the Police Department, following a shouting match this week with another 
councilman over Naranjo's police record. 
</P>
<P>
Councilman Stephen Alexander on Monday proposed an ordinance that would prevent 
anyone convicted of impersonating a police officer -- or of any misdemeanor or 
felony -- from participating in police ride-alongs, an integral part of the 
liaison job. 
</P>
<P>
In 1986, Naranjo, working as a bail bond investigator, was arrested in West 
Covina for impersonating a police officer. He later pleaded no contest and was 
fined $150 and given six months' summary probation. He publicly disclosed his 
record during his 1988 City Council campaign. 
</P>
<P>
Naranjo said Tuesday his decision is not final: "I have received many phone 
calls from the community urging me to stay. I'll make my decision by the end of 
the week." 
</P>
</TEXT>
