<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Auld Leno Syne: For the first time since "The Tonight Show Starring Johnny 
Carson" moved from New York to Los Angeles in 1972, its New Year's Eve special 
will be broadcast live from the Big Apple, in part. 
</P>
<P>
Guest host Jay Leno, stationed in Burbank, will be joined by NBC's Jane Pauley 
in New York on the Dec. 31 show. Pauley will host live coverage of the Times 
Square countdown to midnight. The show will begin taping at 8:30 p.m. for the 
live East Coast broadcast, but will be seen tape-delayed on the West Coast. 
Performing guests include blues legend B.B. King and country singer Dwight 
Yoakum. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Leno 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
