<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ARTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wolf Winners: Violinist Yehudi Menuhin and composer-conductor Luciano Berio 
were named Wednesday as winners of Israel's Wolf Prizes in the arts for 1991. 
</P>
<P>
The awards, which carry $100,000 grants, will be presented in May at the 
Israeli Knesset. Menuhin, 74, who lives in London, has founded his own chamber 
orchestra, directs the Gstaad Festival in Switzerland and is president of the 
Trinity College of Music. Berio, 65, of Siena, Italy, is noted for innovations 
in electronic music. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
