<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF : AQUATIC CENTER'S FEES ASSAILED AS 
EXCLUSIONARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
High fees and a "country club" atmosphere effectively exclude minorities from 
the new $6.5-million Rose Bowl Aquatic Center, the head of the Pasadena NAACP 
charged Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
"We are not faced with the blatant racism of old," said John Kennedy of the 
National Assn. for the Advancement of Colored People. 
</P>
<P>
"The means of exclusion have changed but the end result is the same: 
exclusivity." 
</P>
<P>
Critics said only one of the three pools at the center is shallow, allowing for 
recreation by nonswimmers, and the cost of lessons -- $45 for three weeks -- is 
too high for many poor residents of Northwest Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
The aquatic center, which opened in June, is run by the nonprofit Amateur 
Athletic Foundation. Board member Bill Bogaard disputed the allegations of 
exclusivity, saying that more than 13,000 youngsters, many of them minorities, 
used the pools this summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
December 21, 1990, Friday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Aquatics center -- The Amateur Athletic Foundation was incorrectly identified 
as the operator of the Rose Bowl Aquatics Center in Pasadena in an article 
Thursday. The center is run by the Amateur Athletic Foundation Rose Bowl 
Aquatics Center Board of Pasadena. The Pasadena board added the foundation name 
to its title in recognition of a construction donation. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
